Iteration 2: Proposed new text for skills: SKILL: Always fix by changing repository code (not the runtime environment)
- Do NOT “solve” regressions by pip installing/downgrading packages inside the container; evaluation checks the repo patch.
- Only touch dependency versions if the task explicitly asks for packaging changes (requirements/pyproject/lockfile).

SKILL: Know this repo’s key locations (Jinja2 source layout here)
- Core runtime objects (Undefined, DebugUndefined, StrictUndefined, etc.) live in: src/jinja2/runtime.py (there is no src/jinja2/undefined.py in this repo).
- Attribute/item lookup behavior is driven by:
  - src/jinja2/environment.py: Environment.getattr / Environment.getitem returning env.undefined(obj=..., name=...)
  - src/jinja2/compiler.py: visit_Getattr / visit_Getitem emitting environment.getattr/getitem calls

SKILL: Fast code navigation & search patterns
- Find definitions quickly:
  - rg -n "class DebugUndefined|class Undefined|def __getattr__" src/jinja2
- Jump to relevant context:
  - sed -n 'START,ENDp' src/jinja2/runtime.py
- Find tests that define expected behavior before changing semantics:
  - rg -n "DebugUndefined|StrictUndefined|special_attributes|undefined" tests

SKILL: Patch application best practices (avoid “unrecognized input”)
- Use only standard unified diff format for git apply:
  - Starts with: diff --git a/... b/...
  - Contains: --- a/... and +++ b/...
- Never use non-git markers like “*** Begin Patch / *** End Patch” with git apply.
- After edits, always sanity-check:
  - git diff
  - git status --porcelain

SKILL: Safe file editing from bash (avoid heredoc / argument mistakes)
- When passing args to inline Python, use this exact pattern:
  - python - "$FILE" <<'PY'
    ... use sys.argv[1] ...
    PY
- Avoid mixing heredoc terminators with shell tokens (e.g., don’t put PY "$FILE" on the terminator line).

SKILL: Debugging strategy for core behavior changes (Undefined / DebugUndefined)
- Before changing behavior, read the existing tests that cover it; don’t invent expectations.
- When modifying Undefined.__getattr__:
  - Preserve special/dunder attribute handling exactly as tests expect (introspection attributes like __class__ often must raise AttributeError or behave specially).
  - Don’t blindly change “return None” to raising; confirm what the special-casing is for and which names it applies to.
- When fixing DebugUndefined output:
  - Prefer using existing fields/properties (e.g., _undefined_message, _undefined_name, _undefined_obj, _undefined_hint) rather than ad-hoc formatting.
  - If output must include full expressions like “foo.missing”, confirm how that expression is represented in runtime state (may require hint/name construction elsewhere); use tests to drive.

SKILL: Test workflow that prevents “passes locally, fails full suite”
- Always run targeted failing test first to lock expected behavior:
  - pytest -q tests/test_api.py::TestUndefined::test_debug_undefined -vv
- After fixing, run the full suite (core changes require it):
  - pytest -q
- If you add a new test, ensure it matches existing expectations; never “fix” by weakening tests you added if upstream tests disagree.

SKILL: Minimal, reversible changes
- Make the smallest change that satisfies existing tests.
- If experimenting, keep a quick rollback option:
  - cp file file.bak before edits (but don’t commit backups)
- Ensure code style/typing remains consistent with the surrounding module (type annotations, indentation, imports).

SKILL: Diagnose expectation mismatches using runtime inspection
- If a string representation is wrong, introspect what runtime state is available:
  - print(repr(obj._undefined_name), repr(obj._undefined_obj), repr(obj._undefined_hint))
- Use this to decide whether the fix belongs in __str__ or earlier when creating the Undefined instance (Environment.getattr/getitem or compiler).
